{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c13b2a2-96c5-4406-a218-ef05b18565b6","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since your workload versions likely lag behind the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — only *reinstalls* workloads at their current versions to fix corrupted installations. It won't pull newer versions, so it won't resolve a version mismatch caused by an SDK update.\n\nAfter updating, verify with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, also check that your `.csproj` targets the correct `net9.0-*` (or whichever TFM matches your new SDK).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eaea5f5a-7483-4433-bceb-55c5922e3f78","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the installed SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but does **not** update them to newer versions.\n\nSince the issue is that workloads are out of date after an SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the correct choice.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"F405:3412D:1F692D9:2330710:69E81955"},"id":"f71f3092-9360-4c4c-b7ee-9e9f0d0fd725","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:42:06.306Z","parentId":"83049ec0-4a19-4409-8739-c612dc0cec02"}
